<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="525" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d525">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/426</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SRP1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-22">
                                        <hi rend="italic">April 22, 1918</hi>.</date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received May 8.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p rend="center">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Subject</hi>: Ex-President
                                    <persName>Taft</persName>’s memorandum respecting the
                                requisitioning of Dutch ships<note n="1" xml:id="d525fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1425">p.
                                        1425</ref>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the
                                memorandum on the above subject received recently from the
                                Department of State, which I caused to be circulated in various
                                circles in London.<note n="2" xml:id="d525fn2">According to
                                    despatches from the Consuls at Halifax and Moncton, the
                                    memorandum was communicated by them to local newspapers and
                                    published. (File Nos. 656.119/331 and 334.)</note> I have to-day
                                learned that the Foreign Office being upon the point of despatching
                                a note to Holland on the legal aspect of the affair and <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CLR1">Lord Robert Cecil</persName>
                                not having seen Mr. <persName>Taft</persName>’s opinion, he has
                                asked to be provided with a copy which is now before him, and which
                                no doubt will be of assistance to him in dealing with the matter.
                                Any material of this kind sent to me for distribution is always
                                re-addressed in such manner as to bring about the most useful
                                results.</p>
                            <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SRP1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert P. Skinner</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>